=> UniVariate Analysis - One Numeric Variable: Item_Weight.

1. Create an appropriate plot to visualize the distribution of this variable?

a <- ggplot(market_sales, aes(x = Item_Weight))+
  geom_dotplot(aes(fill =Item_Weight),
               fill = "Light Green",alpha =0.5,
               binwidth = 1/4) +
  ylim(0,4)+
  labs(y = "Count",
       x = "Item Weight",
       title = "A projection of Item Weight") +
  theme_classic()

a

The Dot_plot displays projection of Item_weight.

2.Consider any outliers present in the data.If present, specify the criteria used to identify them and provide a logical explanation for how you handled them ?

mean(market_sales$Item_Weight)
## [1] 13.13443
median(market_sales$Item_Weight)
## [1] 13.3

  • Answer : There are no outliers in the data, as mean and median values are approximately the same.

3.Describe the shape and skewness of the distribution ?

  • This Dot_plot has Symmetric (bell) shaped ,that means a vertical line drawn at the center will form mirror images, with the left half of the graph being the mirror image of the right half of the graph. In the dot plot, this shape is referred to as being a “bell shape” or a “mound”.

  • This Dot_plot has Skewed Right (positively) Distribution - this data plots are found to the right of the graph (toward the larger numeric values). The “tail” of the graph is pulled toward higher positive numbers, or to the right.

The mean typically gets pulled toward the tail, and is greater than the median.

4.Based on your answer to the previous question, decide if it is appropriate to apply a transformation to your data. If no, explain why not. If yes, name the transformation applied and visualize the transformed distribution

  • answer: as mean and median values are approximately the same and,There are no outliers in the data and it has Symmetric (bell) shaped and Skewed Right (positively skewed) distribution.to validate this condition binwidth has been increased.

5.Choose and calculate an appropriate measure of central tendency.

  • answer : We can either choose mean or median measure of central tendency as there are no outliers and the data is symmetric with uniform distribution.If the distribution is symmetric, center is often defined as the mean: mean ~ median

Item_weight_mean <- mean(market_sales$Item_Weight)

Item_weight_medin <-median(market_sales$Item_Weight)

6.Explain why you chose this as your measure of central tendency. Provide supporting evidence for your choice.

  • Measures of Central Tendency provide a summary measure that attempts to describe a whole set of data with a single value that represents the middle or centre of its distribution. in this plot Symmetric (bell) shaped and Skewed Right (positively skewed) distribution,so that there is two main measures of central tendency: the mean, and the median.

ggplot(market_sales, aes(y = Item_Weight)) +

7.Choose and calculate a measure of spread that is appropriate for your chosen measure of central tendency. Explain why you chose this as your measure of spread The preferred measure of central tendency often depends on the shape of the distribution.

  • The preferred measure of central tendency often depends on the shape of the distribution.for distributions that have skewed to the right.For a positively skewed distribution, the mean will always be the highest estimate of central tendency
